<br>
Actually no they don't.<br>
<br>
Look again at the results.<br>
<br>
In all test the mob connects 40% of the time.  We can therefore conclude that Avoidance is UNCHANGED at all AC values.  This fits the hypothesis that Thresher and myself have put forward - that all avoidance is fixed based on class values.<br>
<br>
But look again at the tests, there is a change somewhere between 1080AC and 975AC.  The Avoidance stays the same but the mitigation drops and you start taking 75 damage per hit from a consistant 69 (dude!)<br>
<br>
Again this fits *exactly* the theory.  THe mob is relatively low level and the UPPER cap for the mob is somewhere around 1000AC.  AC past this level has no meaning.  For a higher mo (and other sets of parsed results show this) the AC UPPER cap will be higher.<br>
<br>
This is the point missed by those promoting the theories that there is some fixed, permanent cap.  There isn't.  There is a cap which depends on the level of mob you fight.<br>
<br>
It fits the hypothesis and it fits the empirical evidence.  That's the basis under which you can call something a Fact on scientific principles.<br>
<br>
The theory predicts more.  Keep dropping your Ac till naked.  You will find that the Avoidance doesn;'t change.  The mob will always hit 40% of the time.  but the damage per hit wil continue to rise till at some point (and given the level of mob and my experience of other mobs this will be around 800AC to 850AC) the damage per hit will STOP rising.  This is the LOWER cap.<br>
<br>
(BTW, the existance of this lower cap is what lead some people, including myself, to initially believe AC had little impact *at all* because when Rubicite was the best armour in the game, people simply couldn't get an AC high enough to get to the LOWER cap!)<br>
<br>
Your parses are good and useful but they don't give the conclusion you seem to be saying.<br>
<br>
AC is impacting here, its just only impacting at the lower end because of the low level of the mob.<br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
Eduin <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaxantur.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Axantur</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/9/02 4:34:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1242.topic&index=82>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ubermob tanking</span><hr size=1> hit distribution and frequency and what we can do to manipulate same is the next interesting question; in point of fact, the 1-20 'die' in the damage calculation as has been uncovered is not as random as we might be given to believe.<br>
<br>
the following image was generated with gnuplot, the data is from a logfile i forgot i left on, stretching from level 55 to nearly level 58.  this is all activity in that range, raids included, str from 180-255, dex from 100-180, various ranger ATK buffs sometimes, so on so forth.  it is my unfounded suspicion that these buffs raise the &quot;average ocurring minimum&quot; on the modal (eg DB + (DI * (10..20)) is more common than DB + (DI * (1..10)), and a model of 10 exactly is the most frequent).<br>
<br>
i wrote a quick awk script which produced the frequency of times i hit for each amount.  then used gnuplot to produce a graph.  on the X axis you'll see an amount I hit for.  on the Y axis you'll see the number of times i hit (anything) for that amount.  the results are not as evenly distributed as one might have thought.<br>
<br>
the slash data includes both a Short Sword of the Morning and the paladin Epic, Fiery Defender.<br>
<br>
the pierce data is /only/ a 30/37 velium type lance, which is what i used when i didn't need to bash prior to getting epic.<br>
<br>
the 'all' data is the sum of the two, it seemed useful at the time, but clearly isn't.<br>
<br>
the resulting area under the graph reveals that i'm a paladin.  film at 11.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.mercenary.net/LoadedDice.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
you can see how the slash data is basically comprised of 2 sets of data organized similarly to the pierce data.  this makes the pierce data the most useful for visualizing individual hit distribution.<br>
<br>
so, paying attention to only the pierce data, note the 4 discrete zones produced.<br>
<br>
1) the preamble, a relatively large spike at what we calculate is the weapon's minimum damage.  i seem to recall some patch message ages ago that said we'd hit for minimum more often than missing now.  rounding up the not-quite-zeroes, i guess.<br>
<br>
2) the loading sawtooth.  randonmess isn't, very.  it seems either odd or even modals are statistically less likely.  i'm too lazy to figure out which.  note that the slope is 'generally up' and then 'flattens out' prior to the next zone.<br>
<br>
3) the average.  5,000 froglok scars agree, with any given weapon, if you hit, you're probably hitting for this number.<br>
<br>
4) the trailing slope.  a straight line (the jags in the graph in this area are too small to infer any meaning) down to your max.<br>
<br>
<br>
